In [[economics]], '''bargaining power''' refers to the ability to influence the setting of prices or wages, usually arising from some sort of [[monopoly]] or [[monopsony]] position -- or a non-[[equilibrium]] situation in the [[market]]. The economic actor with more bargaining power has more economic [[freedom]] than those with similar assets.

In virtually all the cases, actors with economic resources or those who control the means of production have greater bargaining power.